    {
      "id": 5282,
      "name": "Claude De Vetter",
      "username": "MedTechCD",
      "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/57b2e6/{size}.png",
      "created_at": "2022-01-25T00:20:07.661Z",
      "cooked": "<p><a class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/alex\">@Alex</a> I think you misunderstood but I\u2019m probably not making my point in a clear way\u2026<br>\nSo if you have reached your maximal available training time per week, you will no longer be able to increase CTL unless you go the \u201cwrong\u201d way and increase intensity. But after a progressing cycle of 6-8 weeks with a \u201csafe\u201d training plan, your FTP should normally be higher. Thus, if you repeat that same cycle with the new and higher FTP, CTL will be very similar but the total amount of \u201cwork done\u201d will be higher because the overall power output is higher. And you will improve again and again.<br>\nI\u2019m not saying that you should do that same thing year round, but a lot of newcomers can. And it will take quite a bit of time before they plateau. People tend to think that they need to increase intensity but intensity is relative to FTP. If you plot a chart with \u201cwork done\u201d, the improvement becomes visible in that chart while it is not showing in the PMC chart.<br>\nBut let\u2019s be clear, base-build-peak is a solid and proven technique that provides a variability in triggers to the body and lifts the results to a higher level.</p>",
      "post_number": 12,
      "post_type": 1,
      "updated_at": "2022-01-25T00:20:07.661Z",
